title: FBI releases new intel on Trump assassination attempt
description: Sky News contributor Kosha Gada analysed newly released FBI background findings on the would-be assassin who shot at US President Donald Trump.  “Allegedly, he’s a they them, a furry,” Ms Gada told Sky News host Rita Panahi.   “We know he was also very high IQ … so that’s maybe an ingredient in that as well.   “They sort of seem to just get captured by this sort of pornographic fetish-type culture on the internet.   “They get sucked into this vortex and then get radicalised."

title: Charlie Kirk’s alleged Killer and Trump's attempted assassins’ bizarre online fetishes
description: Sky News host Rita Panahi highlighted online community and behaviour similarities between Charlie Kirk’s alleged killer and US President Donald Trump’s attempted assassin.  “He did use they them pronouns and was on a website for known for hosting pornographic furry material,” Ms Panahi said.   “Charlie Kirk's alleged killer was also involved in furry culture.”

title: ‘He’ll take the fight to Albo’: Andrew Hastie leadership speculation circulates
description: Former 2GB host Ray Hadley says Andrew Hastie is best equipped to “take the fight” to the Labor government.  “Hastie’s a distinguished ex-serviceman, an officer in the army, he’s from the right, and he’ll take the fight to Penny Wong, to Tony Burke, and most importantly to Albo,” Mr Hadley told Sky News host Sharri Markson.  “He’ll get up to the floor of parliament, and you watch him mix it with them if he’s the leader.”

title: ‘Dear, oh dear’: Ray Hadley blasts ABC over handling of editing controversy
description: Former 2GB host Ray Hadley blasts the ABC over its handling of the editing controversy.  “Media Watch has been a waste of money for the government and the ABC for quite some time,” Mr Hadley told Sky News host Sharri Markson.  “Dead, oh dear.”

title: ‘Nasty’ and ‘cocky’ Anthony Albanese dodges questions regarding Higgins case
description: Sky News host Paul Murray says Prime Minister Anthony Albanese is “nasty” and “cocky” during questioning surrounding the Brittany Higgins case.    “The Prime Minister has been in Western Australia today, he held a cabinet meeting … of course, great expense to the taxpayer, but who cares, other people’s money,” Mr Murray said.  “I want to put a bit of an underline here, about just how nasty and just how cocky the prime minister is.”

title: ‘Infrastructure does not exist’: Australia struggles to keep pace with surging population
description: Sky News host Paul Murray says Australia’s infrastructure is not designed to keep up with the surge in the population.   “Right now, in every single state and capital city, there is a problem if you call triple 0, that an ambulance may or may not turn up quickly,” Mr Murray said.  “There’s not enough room inside the hospitals, why? Because we haven’t built ones that are big enough.  “The infrastructure does not exist, which matches the surges in the Australian population.”

title: ‘Wasteful spending’: Ros Bates under fire for billing taxpayers for milk
description: Sky News host James Macpherson reports that Queensland Minister for Finance and Trade Ros Bates is facing criticism for billing taxpayers for her travel expenses.   “The Queensland trade minister Ros Bates … as finance minister, she was charged with enforcing discipline for responsible spending among LNP members,” Mr Macpherson said.  “Ros Bates, as the trade minister, has done a number of overseas trips in the last 12 months, and you wouldn’t believe what she’s billed taxpayers for.”

title: ‘How was this missed?’: Fury over police failure to act on violent anti-Trump posts
description: Sky News host Rita Panahi questioned why authorities did not intervene earlier despite alarming online posts allegedly linked to Crooks, including extremist anti-government instructions.  “Crooks's political views shifted dramatically left around early 2020,” Ms Panahi said.   “Crooks reportedly called for anti-Trump supporters to conduct terrorism-style attacks against the US government, and he even outlined ways to 'sneak a bomb' into a government building and 'set it off before anyone sees you.   “We’ve got individuals like this posting how-to guides on how to blow up buildings and nothing.”

title: Wilson is ‘making history’ as the first female Victorian Opposition leader
description: Sky News host Sharri Markson says Jess Wilson is “making history” as the first woman to lead the Victorian Liberal Party.  “John Pesutto was never going to win, Brad Battin was making headway, yet Jacinta Allan was still on track to win next year's election,” Ms Markson said.  “Jessica Wilson is now the party's final hope.”

title: ​ABC is so ‘blinded’ by its own ‘bias’: Sharri Marson
description: Sky News host Sharri Markson calls out ABC for often suppressing “lines of inquiry” that don’t suit its “political narrative”.  “They effectively absolved themselves, declaring there's no serious problem of bias at the public broadcaster,”  Ms Markson said.  “The ABC is so blinkered by its own self-importance, so blinded by its own bias, that it refuses to recognise the truth.”

title: Wilson had the ‘numbers’ to be elected ‘months ago’ as Vic Liberal leader
description: The Australian’s Victorian Political Editor Anthony Galloway says Victorian Liberal Leader Jess Wilson could have been elected “months ago,” as she “had the numbers”.  “The only hold up was Wilson, that she wasn't willing to go yet, she’s a 35-year-old with a young son,” Mr Galloway told Sky News host Peta Credlin.  “She had many years potentially before she had to put her hand up.”

title: ‘Disgraceful’: Migration reaches unprecedented high
description: One Nation Leader Pauline Hanson says Australians have had a “gutful” of mass migration.  “This government has continued with high migration, only to prop up their poor ability to look after the economy,” Ms Hanson told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “That’s disgraceful.”

title: Bank CEO calls for cuts to migration to make housing ‘more affordable’
description: Sky News Host Caleb Bond says Commonwealth Bank CEO Matt Comyn blew the “whistle” on the issue of mass migration and its impact on the housing crisis.  “Here, you have the CEO of one of the biggest businesses in Australia saying we need to cut migration in order to make housing more affordable,” Mr Bond said.  “That’s a really significant moment.”

title: ​ The Liberal Party is in my ‘blood’: Jess Wilson
description: Victorian Opposition Leader Jess Wilson says the Liberal Party is in her “blood” in response to critics who doubt her ability as the first woman to lead Victorian Liberals.  “I might be a new politician in my first term, but I'm not new to politics. I’ve worked in this extensively,” Ms Wilson told Sky News host Peta Credlin.  “Its values, its aspirations are as relevant today as they were when the party was established.  “I believe I can translate those to the Victorian people today and the policies we can deliver.”

title: First woman to lead Victorian Liberals will provide ‘credible alternative’ in next election
description: Victorian Opposition Leader Jess Wilson has become the first woman to lead Victorian Liberals as she states the party needs to take a “new direction”.  “We needed to be very clear that we had a broad set of priorities that we could take to the next election,” Ms Wilson told Sky News host Peta Credlin.  “First and foremost, around the failing Victorian economy.  “I can take that broad agenda around the economy … to the next election and provide that credible alternative.”
